Functional dispersion in IBC_grass.noNDD

This document describes IBC_grass.noNDD, using functional dispersion as the focal biodiversity metric.

2 Fitting the model

2.1 Main effect

The main effect represents the relationship between diversity and total biomass without taking into account the richness treatment.

To produce this model, we use the call:

brm(formula = total.biomass ~ -1 + Stage + Stage:FDis,
    data = IBC_grass.noNDD)

A summary table of the result:

2.1.1 Posterior predictive checks

We next use posterior predictive checks (PPC) to judge the fit of the model. These compare the real data to the posterior distribution, conditioned on the observed data.

The density of both the real data (y, black line), and from fitted draws of the models (y_rep, blue lines).

brms::pp_check(IBC_grass.noNDD$mainEffect[[1]]) +
    labs(x = "Total biomass") +
    theme_bw()



The second PPC for the main effect is the average prediction (y_rep) for each real datapoint (y). A line indicates a 1:1 correspondence for reference.

brms::pp_check(IBC_grass.noNDD$mainEffect[[1]],
               type = 'scatter_avg_grouped',
               group = "Stage") +
    geom_abline(intercept = 0,
                slope = 1) +
    labs(title = "Realized total biomass to average predicted total biomass") +
    theme_bw()



Lastly, we inspect the highest-density interval (HDI) for each effect within the model. This characterizes the uncertainty of our posterior distributions. Highest-density intervals can be thought of as credibility intervals. A nice graphic explaining them can be found here. I use the 89% HDI as recommended by Kruschke (2014), see here.

sjPlot::plot_model(IBC_grass.noNDD$mainEffect[[1]],
                   title = "89% Highest-density intervals")

2.2 Treatment effects

For the treatment effect we incorporate the different richness treatments into the model, giving each combination a different intercept and slope.

We use the formula:

brm(formula = total.biomass ~ -1 + Ninitial:Stage + Ninitial:Stage:FDis,
    data = IBC_grass.noNDD)

Note that both Ninitial and Stage are treated as categorical variables. Further, because both the monocultures and the singleton 64-species community have no variation with respect to realized diversity, they are omitted from this model.

3 Plotting the final model fits

And now I plot the final fits:

extract_significances_mainEffect <- function(model_, measure_)
{
    hdi_ <- bayestestR::hdi(model_) %>%
        mutate(significant = !(0 >= CI_low & 0 <= CI_high))

    hdi_ <- hdi_ %>%
        filter(str_detect(Parameter, measure_)) %>%
        mutate(Stage = ifelse(str_detect(Parameter, "metacommunity"),
                              "metacommunity",
                              "isolation"))

    hdi_ <- hdi_ %>%
        mutate(Stage = as.factor(Stage)) %>%
        select(Stage, significant)
  
  hdi_ <- hdi_ %>% 
    mutate(Stage = fct_relevel(Stage, c("metacommunity", "isolation")))

    return(hdi_)
}

extract_significances_treatmentEffect <- function(model_, measure_)
{
    hdi_ <- bayestestR::hdi(model_) %>%
        mutate(significant = !(0 >= CI_low & 0 <= CI_high))

    hdi_ <- hdi_ %>%
        filter(str_detect(Parameter, measure_)) %>%
        mutate(Stage = ifelse(str_detect(Parameter, "metacommunity"),
                              "metacommunity",
                              "isolation")) %>%
        mutate(Ninitial = str_extract(Parameter, "\\d+"))

    hdi_ <- hdi_ %>%
        mutate(Stage = as.factor(Stage),
               Ninitial = as.factor(Ninitial)) %>%
        select(Stage, Ninitial, significant)
  
  hdi_ <- hdi_ %>% 
    mutate(Stage = fct_relevel(Stage, c("metacommunity", "isolation")))

    return(hdi_)
}

data <- IBC_grass.noNDD %>% unnest(data)
mainEffect_ <- IBC_grass.noNDD$mainEffect[[1]]
treatmentEffect_ <- IBC_grass.noNDD$treatmentEffect[[1]]

mainEffect <- data %>%
    group_by(Stage) %>%
    data_grid(FDis) %>%
    add_fitted_draws(mainEffect_) %>%
    inner_join(extract_significances_mainEffect(mainEffect_, "FDis"))

treatmentEffect <- data %>%
    filter(Ninitial %in% levels(treatmentEffect_$data$Ninitial)) %>%
    droplevels() %>%
    group_by(Ninitial, Stage) %>%
    data_grid(FDis) %>%
    add_fitted_draws(treatmentEffect_) %>%
    inner_join(extract_significances_treatmentEffect(treatmentEffect_, "FDis"))

ggplot() +
    geom_point(data = data,
               aes(x = FDis,
                   y = total.biomass,
                   color = Ninitial),
               alpha = 0.9) +
    stat_lineribbon(data = mainEffect,
                    aes(x = FDis,
                        y = .value,
                        group = Stage,
                        linetype = significant),
                    alpha = 0.5,
                    show.legend = FALSE) +
    stat_lineribbon(data = treatmentEffect,
                    aes(x = FDis,
                        y = .value,
                        color = Ninitial,
                        group = Ninitial,
                        linetype = significant),
                    alpha = 0.5,
                    show.legend = FALSE) +
    scale_linetype_manual(values = c("twodash", "solid")) +
    facet_grid(. ~ Stage) +
    labs(x = "FDis",
         y = "Total biomass",
         color = "Richness\ntreatment") +
    scale_color_viridis(discrete = TRUE) +
    scale_fill_brewer(palette = "Greys") +
    theme_bw()

Ribbons indicate 95%, 80%, and 50% credibility intervals. The black line represents the main effect, omitting the richness treatments. Dashed lines have estimates that include 0 within their 89% HDI.
